          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Assad loyalist ambush</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-dec-27-2.jpg" alt="Assad loyalist ambush" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Syria is finding itself in a volatile and complex transition period. 14 interior ministry troops were killed in an <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-27-dec-2024-3-ambush" target="_blank">ambush</a> near Tartous, a pro-Assad stronghold, marking a direct challenge to al-Sharaa's authority. Reports claim that the security forces clashed with the military troops when they sought to arrest a former officer who was linked to a notorious prison. On Thursday, the security forces launched an operation and claimed that the troops had been neutralized in the Tartous countryside and were pursuing others.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Tensions are high as the country is fractured, and trying to unite isn't easy. Pro-Assad loyalists, particularly from the Alawite minority, feared retaliation for alleged war crimes committed under Assad's rule. The Kurds in Syria have also had their recent <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-27-dec-2024-4-concerns" target="_blank">concerns</a> as they seek to protect their political gains. Calls for a general amnesty from Alawite leaders are unlikely to gain traction, given public demands for justice. The ruling government has pledged to protect minorities but faces criticism after incidents like the <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-27-dec-2024-5-burning" target="_blank">burning</a> of a Christmas tree.​</p>
        </mj-text>
